		<Title>Lesson 17. Symbols on Home Row, Top Row and Number Row</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>This lesson helps you practice typing symbols on the Home row, Top row and Number row with your right pinky finger only. If you can't remember the correct layout of the keys, please get back to Lesson 15 and 16.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#;|'|;|p|;|[|;|]|;|0|;|-|;|=</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
		<LessonTime>4</LessonTime>
	</Lesson>
	<Lesson>
		<Title>Lesson 18. Capitals (with SHIFT key)</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>Please note that all letters in this lesson are in capitals. When you want to type a capital letter, hold down the Shift key while typing the letter key. On your main keyboard, there are two Shift keys: the left Shift and the right Shift. They are all placed on the second row from the bottom of the keyboard. To be more specific, the left Shift key is to the left of the Z key and the right Shift key is to the right of the Forward Slash key.
Use your left or right pinky finger to press the Shift key. When you want to type a letter for which you have to use a finger on your left hand, just use your right pinky finger to press the Shift key, and vice versa.
For example, you want to type an A (in capital), hold down the right Shift key with your right pinky finger, then press A with your left pinky finger.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#A|S|D|F|G|H|J|K|L|Q|W|E|R|T|Y|U|I|O|P|Z|X|C|V|B|N|M</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
		<LessonTime>4</LessonTime>
	</Lesson>
	<Lesson>
		<Title>Lesson 19. Symbols on Number Row - Left Hand with SHIFT key</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>When you combine the Shift key respectively with the 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 keys, you will have the following symbols: the exclamation point, the at sign, the numeric sign, the dollar sign and the percent sign.
You should place your fingers properly as you have learned from Lesson 14. For example, to type a at sign @, hold down the right Shift key with your right pinky finger, then press the number 2.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#a|1|!|s|2|@|d|3|#|f|4|$|g|5|%</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
		<LessonTime>3</LessonTime>
	</Lesson>
	<Lesson>
		<Title>Lesson 20. Symbols on Number Row - Right Hand with SHIFT key</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>When you combine the Shift key respectively with the 6, 7, 8, 9, 0 keys, you will have the following symbols: the circumflex accent, the ampersand, the asterish, the left parenthesis, and the right parenthesis.
You should place your fingers properly as you have learned form Lesson 14. For example, to type a left parenthesis, hold down the left Shift key with your left pinky finger, then press the number 9.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#|h|6|^|j|7|&amp;|k|8|*|l|9|(|;|0|)</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
		<LessonTime>3</LessonTime>
	</Lesson>
	<Lesson>
		<Title>Lesson 21. Symbols on Home Row and Bottom Row, Right Hand with SHIFT key</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>On the Home row, when you press the Shift key and the Semi-colon key, you will have a colon; press the Shift key and the Single Quote key to type a double quotation mark. On the Bottom row, press Shift and and Comma to type a less than sign; press Shift and Period to type a greater than sign; press Shift and Forward Slash to type a question mark.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#k|,#|l|.|;|/|k|&lt;|l|&gt;|;|:|?|'|"</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
		<LessonTime>3</LessonTime>
		<KeysToType/>
	</Lesson>
	<Lesson>
		<Title>Lesson 22. Symbols on Home Row, Top Row and Number Row</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>On the Top row, to the right of the P key, you will find the Left and the Right Bracket keys. Press the Shift key and one of these keys to type a left or right curly bracket. To the right of the number 0 on the Top row, you will find the Hyphen and the Equal keys. Press the Shift key and one of these keys to type a low line or a plus sign.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#;|:|'|"|p|[|{|]|}|0|)|-|_|=|+</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
		<LessonTime>3</LessonTime>
		<KeysToType/>
	</Lesson>
	<Lesson>
		<Title>Lesson 23. Common Letters, Numbers and Punctuation Marks</Title>
		<Author>Sao Mai Training Team</Author>
		<Description>This is the last lesson in the "Introduction to the Keyboard Layout" package. If you cannot remember exactly what you have learned, especially the rules to place your fingers correctly, please get back to related lessons to practice until you really get used to all the keys on your keyboard.
In this lesson, you can practice typing all of the most common letters, numbers and punctuation marks used in daily document editing. This also helps you review and self-evaluate your own level.
Press F2 to repeat the current full text to type, F3 to read the word to type, F4 to read the character to type and F5 to temporarily switch between different speaking as typing modes.</Description>
		<ExpectedPoint>85</ExpectedPoint>
		<TextToType>#a|b|c|d|e|f|g|h|i|j|k|l|m|n|o|p|q|r|s|t|u|v|w|x|y|z|1|2|3|4|5|6|7|8|9|0|k|,|l|.|;|/|:|?|'|"|1|!|2|@|9|(|0|)</TextToType>
		<ExpectedSpeed>40</ExpectedSpeed>
